You need not be in the least afraid of sending too often!! You may be very sure that a contribution from you is more welcome and delightful to me than I dare express to the most suspicious of women.<note>CD was eager to have contributions from his “Dear Scheherazade” (Pilgrim Letters 6, p. 545): Gaskell valued Household Words’ ethos and CD’s prompt payment. The relationship was uneasy, though: Gaskell accused CD of stealing one of her ghost stories (Pilgrim <hi rend="italic">Letters</hi> 6, pp. 545-6 &amp;amp; nn); CD altered without authorisation a reference to Pickwick in “Our Society at Cranford”, <hi rend="italic">Household Words</hi>, 13 Dec 51, IV, 265 (see Pilgrim <hi rend="italic">Letters</hi> 6, pp. 548-9); and both had problems over the writing and serialisation of North and South (see Pilgrim <hi rend="italic">Letters</hi> 7).</note> You shall have a Proof of this MS, if you will be so kind as to correct it.<note>“Visiting at Cranford”, <hi rend="italic">Household Words</hi>, 3 Apr 52, V, 55.</note> I thought I had, myself, gone carefully over the last;<note>“A Love Affair at Cranford”, Household Words, 3 Jan 52, IV, 349.</note> – but upon my word it made me cry so, that I might as well have left it alone for any mechanical eyesight that5 remained to me.
